				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-466570/scp-1600#post-4220100</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Mon, 15 Apr 2019 20:56:28 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Elogee FishTruck</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>4037075</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Perhaps I am missing the point of the article, and it is very well written for when it was posted, but I can't see myself upvoting it. It's a philosopher's cheese, yes, but there simply isn't enough for me to be invested or really wonder about it, and the test logs are too disconnected for me to ponder shout what connects them all. They're all safe to eat and they're all &quot;cheese&quot;? What does cheese even mean?</p> <p>I personally like the explanation <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/anqxyr" ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=966960&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1555361788" alt="anqxyr" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=966960)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/anqxyr" >anqxyr</a></span> gave in his author page, where a factory owner tries to make a philosopher's stone but the result is the cheese. That, to me, would lead to something interesting if that was explored. Sadly, I'll have to give this a no-vote, as there's nothing for me to really hate for a downvote but not enough good for an upvote.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
